ates of the Ripple Effects of Minimum Wage Laws -- t12. Employment Effects of Higher Minimum Wages: A State-by-State Comparative Analysis -- t13. Comments on Aaron Yelowitz, "Santa Fe's Living Wage Ordinance and the Labor Market" -- t14. Detecting the Effects of Living Wage Laws: A Comment on Neumark and Adams -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex -- tAbout the Authors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn early 2007, there were approximately 140 living wage ordinances in place throughout the United States. Communities around the country frequently debate new proposals of this sort. Additionally, as a result of ballot initiatives, twenty-nine states and the District of Columbia, representing nearly 70 percent of the total U.S. population, maintain minimum wage standards above those set by the federal minimum wage.In A Measure of Fairness, Robert Pollin, Mark Brenner, Jeannette Wicks-Lim, and Stephanie Luce assess how well living wage and minimum wage regulations in the United States serve the workers they are intended to help. Opponents of such measures assert that when faced with mandated increases in labor costs, businesses will either lay off workers, hire fewer low-wage employees in the future, replace low-credentialed workers with those having better qualifications or, finally, even relocate to avoid facing the increased costs being imposed on them.The authors give an overview of living wage and minimum wage implementation in Louisiana, New Mexico, Arizona, California, Massachusetts, and Connecticut to show how these policies play out in the paychecks of workers, in the halls of legislature, and in business ledgers. Based on a decade of research, this volume concludes that living wage laws and minimum wage increases have been effective policy interventions capable of bringing significant, if modest, benefits to the people they were intended to help.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aLiving wage movementzUnited States. 0aMinimum wagezUnited States. 4aGeneral Economics. 4aLabor History. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Labor.2bisacsh1 aBrenner, Mark, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aLuce, Stephanie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aPollin, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150172952240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501729522423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501729522/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK